                                       <div class="service col-md-offset-2 col-md-8 col-xs-12">
                                          <div class="text-font-family service-desc wow fadeInUp animated" style="visibility: visible; ">
                                            <p class="dropcap"> The last few days have been a blur for Saikiran Krishnamurthy whose job is to make sure that the goods you order on Flipkart reach you in time. In the last two weeks, heâs been to Flipkartâs offices from Dankuni in Kolkata to Bhiwandi in Maharashtra. He made over 20 such visits, talking to the rank and file and taking stock of things. </p><p>

Krishnamurthy, a former McKinsey consultant cannot stop showing pictures of iPhone packages, electronics goods and even kitchenware, all packed up and lying across Flipkartâs massive warehouses --17 of them in all and with a spread of over four million square feet in expanse. Over one million square feet of warehouse space was added over just past few weeks, Krishnamurthy says. The warehouses are bursting at seams. âEverything at the supply chain is working at five to ten times the average scale.â </p>



										</div></div>
									<div class="col-md-offset-2 col-md-8 col-xs-12">
										<div class="text-font-family service-desc wow fadeInUp animated" style="visibility: visible; ">
											<img src='https://factordaily.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Saikiran_Krishnamurthy_Flipkart.jpg' />
											<cite class="wow fadeInUp" style="visibility: hidden; animation-name: none;">Saikiran Krishnamurthy, Head - Ekart, Fulfillment and Customer Support, is the owner of four million sq. ft. warehouse space. Owner, as in, responsible for all delivery operations. Photo: Rajesh Subramanian.</cite>
										</div>
									</div>
									<div class="service col-md-offset-2 col-md-8 col-xs-12">
										<div class="text-font-family service-desc wow fadeInUp animated" style="visibility: visible; ">



<p>

E-kart, the logistics arm of Flipkart that Krishnamurthy oversees, serves 5,000 pincodes in 700 cities. E-kart employs more than 30,000 people and also uses third party logistics players like Bluedart to deliver orders. âOur supply chain is built to serve with 99% reliability,â he tells us. Krishnamurthy has even put in place a Plan B of sorts, in case there is there are floods, heavy rains or a natural calamity. Heâs been poring over weather reports and flight charts to book cargo space for Flipkartâs goods. </p><p>

Every time a package gets out for delivery in a warehouse, it has to pass six checks and a machine prints out a pink colored slip. The six checks include packaging, product specifications, product ratings, return ratio of the item, the sellerâs ability to fulfil the order, and committed timelines.</p><p>

The entire process is powered by an algorithm developed by a team of Flipkartâs data scientists, which ensures that all variable factors including cancellations and quality are captured and accounted for. The promise is that each of the packages with âFlipkart Assuredâ badge will be delivered within two to four days of the order. </p>


												</div></div>
							<div class="col-md-offset-2 col-md-8 col-xs-12">
								<div class="text-font-family service-desc wow fadeInUp animated" style="visibility: visible; ">
									<img src='https://factordaily.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Flipkart_Story_Inside_Pic9.jpg' />
									<cite class="wow fadeInUp" style="visibility: hidden; animation-name: none;">âWishmasterâ Ramesh has been hard at work on all BBD 2016 days and leaves Flipkart's HSR Layout âfulfilment centreâ (read: warehouse) in Bangalore for deliveries on Wednesday. Photo: Rajesh Subramanian</cite>
								</div>
							</div>
							
							
							<div class="service col-md-offset-2 col-md-8 col-xs-12">
								<div class="text-font-family service-desc wow fadeInUp animated" style="visibility: visible; ">
									<p>

âThe pink slip for each package is like getting fired from the warehouse,â Krishnamurthy says jokingly. On Wednesday, we visited Flipkartâs delivery hub near HSR Layout in Bengaluru. Wishmasters, as Flipkart calls its delivery staff, are working double shifts to clear packages from the hub. </p><p>

Flipkart has added nearly 10,000 temporary workers to its delivery workforce of 30,000 across India to help with last mile delivery during BBD 2016.. This includes local kirana shop owners and people who had spare time to deliver packages and earn some money. âItâs an Uber for delivery,â says Krishnamurthy.</p><p> 

On Thursday evening, the last day of the sale, Krishnamurthy told FactorDaily on the phone that the company has already delivered nearly one million orders. But the job is still far from finished. With holidays coming up, a lot of goods are likely to pile up because customers donât tend to be at home. </p>
